					{ q: "Does this mean I'm legally liable for what my agents do?", a: "You are accountable for the limits you set. If an agent acts within the spending cap, the allowed recipient list, and the permissions you biometrically authorised — that is an action you authorised. That is the same relationship you have with an employee acting within their delegated authority. The difference is that the chain of authorisation is now cryptographically provable, not a matter of disputed memory." },
					{ q: "What if an AI model produces bad output that causes harm?", a: "The model proposes. The blockchain decides. An AI model can suggest a transaction to a bad actor, but if that actor's address isn't on the approved recipient list you signed, the Move contract rejects it. The model operates inside a cryptographic box whose walls were drawn by your biometric. It cannot break the box — regardless of what it generates." },
